<DOC><DOCNO> AP890828-0001 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-89 2340EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-HelmsleyTrial     08-28 0283</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Helmsley Trial,0290</SECOND><HEAD>Jury Ends Day 3 In Helmsley Deliberations</HEAD><BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The jury in Leona Helmsley's tax evasion trialended a third day of deliberations without a verdict Monday afterrehearing testimony from liquor salesmen who said they gavekickbacks to the hotel magnate.   The jurors in Manhattan's federal court deliberated 8{ hours inthe third day of discussions. They had deliberated about 15 hoursover the weekend.   Mrs. Helmsley, 69, is charged with evading $1.2 million infederal taxes by charging personal expenses, including renovationsat her Connecticut mansion, to her businesses.   Her co-defendants, former aides Turco and Joseph Licari, arecharged with assisting in the scheme.   Mrs. Helmsley is charged with 41 of the 47 counts in theindictment, including conspiracy to defraud the Internal RevenueService, tax evasion, signing false personal returns, aiding in thefiling of false corporate returns, mail fraud and extortionconspiracy.   The panel on Monday asked to rehear testimony from two liquorsalesmen who testified that they were forced to kick back apercentage of their sales to keep accounts at Helmsley hotels.   The testimony relates to the most serious charge against Mrs.Helmsley, conspiracy to commit extortion, which carries a 20-yearprison sentence upon conviction.   The jurors also asked to hear the portion of her attorney'sclosing argument which described the payments as rebates and theprosecutor's rebuttal on that issue.   Judge John Walker Jr., however, told them they could not hear theclosing arguments because they are not considered evidence.   The jury has been sequestered since closing arguments beganWednesday. They heard from 44 prosecution witnesses and four defensewitnesses during the two-month trial.</TEXT></DOC>